Vectors

A vector is an object that has both a magnitude and a direction. Geometrically, we can picture a vector as a directed line segment, whose length is the magnitude of the vector and with an arrow indicating the direction. The direction of the vector is from its tail to its head.

A vector in a simple term can be considered as a single-dimensional array. With respect to Python, a vector is a one-dimensional array of lists. It occupies the elements in a similar manner as that of a Python list.

Lists are 1 dimensional data

In[1]:
lst_data = [45,67,89]
In[12]:
str_data = ["Raman","Thaman","Baman"]

Basic Arithmetic Operations

In[]:
In[]:
'''
lst1 = [4,5,6]
lst2 = [3,4,5]
arr1 = np.array(lst1)
arr2 = np.array(lst2)

# Addition of vectors
add_arrs = arr1 + arr2 # output: [7,9,11]

#Subtraction of vectors
sub_arrs = arr1 - arr2 #output: [1,1,1]

#Multiplication of vectors
mul_arrs = arr1 * arr2 #output: [12,20,30]

#Division of vectors
div_arrs = arr1 / arr2 #output: [1.33,1.25,1.2]

#Dot product
dot_arrs = arr1.dot(arr2) #output: 62

# scalar mutliplication
sc = 5
sc_mul = arr1*5 #output: [20,25,30]

Matrix

A matrix is a two-dimensional data structure where numbers are arranged into rows and columns.

In[7]:
d2 = np.array([[1,2],[1,2]])
d2
Out[7]:
array([[1, 2],
       [1, 2]])
In[9]:
d3 = np.array([[1,2,3],[1,2,5]])
d3
Out[9]:
array([[1, 2, 3],
       [1, 2, 5]])
